    <item>
      <title>OpenAI Launches Safety Fellowship Hours After New Yorker Exposé — $200K Stipends for External Researchers While Three Internal Safety Teams Stay Dead</title>
      <link>https://chatforest.com/guides/openai-safety-fellowship-after-new-yorker-investigation/</link>
      <guid>https://chatforest.com/guides/openai-safety-fellowship-after-new-yorker-investigation/</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 08 Apr 2026 23:50:00 &#43;0000</pubDate>
      <description>On April 6, 2026, OpenAI announced a Safety Fellowship offering external researchers $3,850/week stipends and $15,000/month in compute to study AI safety at Constellation in Berkeley. The announcement arrived hours after Ronan Farrow&#39;s New Yorker investigation detailed how OpenAI dissolved three internal safety teams in two years and dropped safety from its IRS filings. The fellowship mirrors Anthropic&#39;s existing Fellows Program — identical stipends, identical compute — but routes safety work through external researchers rather than rebuilding internal infrastructure. Ronan Farrow noted the timing publicly. An OpenAI representative told Farrow&#39;s team: &#39;What do you mean by existential safety? That&#39;s not, like, a thing.&#39;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Project Glasswing: Anthropic Deploys Claude Mythos to Find Zero-Days in Every Major OS and Browser — With Apple, Microsoft, Google, and 9 More Partners</title>
      <link>https://chatforest.com/guides/anthropic-mythos-project-glasswing-cybersecurity/</link>
      <guid>https://chatforest.com/guides/anthropic-mythos-project-glasswing-cybersecurity/</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 08 Apr 2026 23:45:00 &#43;0000</pubDate>
      <description>On April 7, 2026, Anthropic officially previewed Claude Mythos — the model leaked in March — through Project Glasswing, a cybersecurity initiative pairing the unreleased frontier model with 12 founding partners including Apple, Microsoft, Google, Amazon, Nvidia, CrowdStrike, and the Linux Foundation. Mythos has already identified thousands of zero-day vulnerabilities in every major operating system and browser, including a 27-year-old OpenBSD TCP crash bug and a 16-year-old FFmpeg flaw that fuzzers hit five million times without catching. The model chains 4-5 vulnerabilities together to build full exploits — including Linux kernel root escalation and browser sandbox escapes. Anthropic is committing $100M in usage credits and $4M in open-source donations. The model will not be released publicly. Security researcher Nicholas Carlini says he&#39;s &#39;found more bugs in the last couple of weeks than in the rest of my life combined.&#39;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>The Enterprise AI Power Shift: Anthropic Takes 40% of LLM Spend While OpenAI Falls to 27% — And Both Are Racing to IPO</title>
